After the controversies subsided, Quayle declared his independence from his Bush handlers, saying he would be his own man. Democrats portrayed Quayle during the campaign as a lightweight, a man with little or no legislative accomplishments, untested and unqualified to be a heartbeat away from the presidency. , a GOP consultant who worked with the Bush campaign, says Bush is likely to give Quayle a more active role in the administration than he had in the campaign. Dan Quayle has contributed nothing in the way of staff to the Bush campaign. 